04676nam a22006975i 9780691204246DE-B159720200826040535.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||200826t20202006nju    fo  d z      eng d  a97806912042467 a10.1515/97806912042462doi  a(DE-B1597)544948  a(OCoLC)1159420724  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anjucUS-NJ 4aHD82b.T518 2020eb 7aBIO0210002bisacsh04a330/.092aB2231 aTignor, Robert L., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aW. Arthur Lewis and the Birth of Development Economics /cRobert L. Tignor. 1aPrinceton, NJ : bPrinceton University Press, c[2020] 4cÂ©2006  a1 online resource (336 p.) :b10 b/w illus.  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aPrinceton Legacy Library00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIllustrations -- tPreface -- tINTRODUCTION -- tCHAPTER 1. Getting Started: Education and Race -- tCHAPTER 2. The Colonial Office -- tCHAPTER 3. Unlimited Supplies of Labor -- tCHAPTER 4. The Gold Coast -- tCHAPTER 5. Ghana's Chief Economic Adviser, 1957-58 -- tCHAPTER 6. Ghana: Part 2 -- tCHAPTER 7. The West Indies, 1959-63 -- tCHAPTER 8. The Princeton Years, 1963-91 -- tCONCLUSION -- tBibliography -- tIndex 0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aW. Arthur Lewis was one of the foremost intellectuals, economists, and political activists of the twentieth century. In this book, the first intellectual biography of Lewis, Robert Tignor traces Lewis's life from its beginnings on the small island of St. Lucia to Lewis's arrival at Princeton University in the early 1960s. A chronicle of Lewis's unfailing efforts to promote racial justice and decolonization, it provides a history of development economics as seen through the life of one of its most important founders.If there were a record for the number of "firsts" achieved by one man during his lifetime, Lewis would be a contender. He was the first black professor in a British university and also at Princeton University and the first person of African descent to win a Nobel Prize in a field other than literature or peace. His writings, which included his book The Theory of Economic Growth, were among the first to describe the field of development economics.Quickly gaining the attention of the leadership of colonized territories, he helped develop blueprints for the changing relationship between the former colonies and their former rulers. He made significant contributions to Ghana's quest for economic growth and the West Indies' desire to create a first-class institution of higher learning serving all of the Anglophone territories in the Caribbean.This book, based on Lewis's personal papers, provides a new view of this renowned economist and his impact on economic growth in the twentieth century. It will intrigue not only students of development economics but also anyone interested in colonialism and decolonization, and justice for the poor in third-world countries.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Aug 2020) 0aAfrican American economistsvBiography. 0aDevelopment economics. 0aEconomic development. 0aEconomistszUnited StatesvBiography. 7aBIOGRAPHY & AUTOBIOGRAPHY / Social Scientists & Psychologists.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPUP eBook-Package 2000-2015z978311066258040uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780691204246zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780691204246423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780691204246.jpg  a978-3-11-066258-0  PUP eBook-Package 2000-2015c2000d2015  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK